text: ...created draft of the geologic map, & took gigapans. We'll begin comparing maps w/ 2010 D-RATS field data team in July. Thx for following!
This field activity is complete! We completed all of the proposed work, covered the entire field area, collected ~50 kg of samples... (cont)
@SpaceAndCoffee It's an intrusive igneous body that's unrelated to the igneous body itself. So yes, without the intrusive rock, it could be.
@SpaceAndCoffee Simple terms: a rock found in a rock! Here it would be older rock incorporated into the magma while it was still fluid.
Barbara has a newly found talent of finding xenoliths. Here are both halves of the one from today. http://t.co/jr4V2g7SzU
Three team members not pictured in previous post will be mapping using only 2010 Desert RATS field data.
Field team using traditional field geology approaches: (left to right) Jim, Barbara, Peggy, Dean, Debra, & Jake. http://t.co/st0c2VRx8S

Today we are consolidating everyone's data to start creating the geological map for the study area. http://t.co/Gqpl0jBqtZ
Barbara & Debra work together to map an outcrop. Barbara found a xenolith at this site. http://t.co/FZi92UlOpi
Dr. Eppler looking at sample thru a 10X hand lens to identify different lava flows by mineralogy characterization. http://t.co/8ItqVHfsq7
Peggy hammering off a sample of the lava flow for documentation. http://t.co/Baa75YqfCn
Panorama yesterday. We walked down the main ridge of our map area & converged on a couple of candidate hypotheses. http://t.co/LicbolQXJX
Jake characterizing one of the sample sites by collecting GPS data and describing the mineralogy. http://t.co/oLWuwozOQy

Three flow fronts in the area that we investigated today. http://t.co/Iu69rCQZSm
This is funded by a MMAMA (Moon Mars Analog Mission Analysis) NASA Science Mission Directorate grant & builds on science done @ D-RATS 2010.
Debra & Peggy visit a 2nd suspected dike to the south of our study area. Colton Crater is in the background. http://t.co/QE6DlRw4f8
@BarryFawbear Arizona! An area around 50 miles north of Flagstaff called Black Point Lava Flow. Beautiful and full of amazing geology.
Unexpected dike that wasn't obvious from imagery data. (Lava that flowed vertically thru crack in existing material) http://t.co/wjKo0RVS5x
@VolcanoCowboy Maybe you could call them #rockstars
Dean, Jake, and Jim looking NW over the mapping area and hypothesizing about what happened here. #geologyrocks #DRATS http://t.co/4cloNN5VeG
Big bomb in-place. "Bombs" are thrown out of volcanoes during the course of the eruption. #geology http://t.co/vu2UVk71i8
The first day's shoe casualty that required in-field maintenance. Always be prepared and check your gear. http://t.co/skPDepLjXP
We're comparing mapping conducted by field team using traditional geology approaches w/mapping from separate team only using 2010 field data
Very good 1st day in the field! We found some interesting lava flow outcrops with large crystals that we hadn't seen before!
Field gear! http://t.co/cWUwu0DMRV
The 1g Lunar Rover training vehicle (Geologic Rover, or Grover) that we used in D-RATS 2003. http://t.co/4ZWpwFzDfe
Our team of 6 includes 4 geologists, 1 engineer, and 1 astronaut.
